        <section class="prose mt-10">
          <h2>How to read and convert military time</h2>
          <p>Military time is a 24‑hour clock format commonly used by the military, aviation, hospitals, emergency services, and international schedules. Instead of using AM and PM, hours run from 00 to 23.</p>

          <h3>Basic rules</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Military time is written as four digits: <strong>HHMM</strong> (hours and minutes).</li>
            <li><strong>0000</strong> is midnight (start of the day).</li>
            <li><strong>1200</strong> is noon.</li>
            <li><strong>2359</strong> is one minute before midnight.</li>
            <li>Sometimes <strong>2400</strong> is used to mark the end of the day.</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>Formula: military → standard time</h3>
          <div class="formula-box text-sm">
            <p><strong>Given:</strong> military time HHMM</p>
            <ol>
              <li>Split into hour and minute: \( H = \lfloor \text{HHMM} / 100 \rfloor \), \( M = \text{HHMM} \bmod 100 \).</li>
              <li>If \( H = 0 \): standard hour = 12, period = AM.</li>
              <li>If \( 1 \le H \le 11 \): standard hour = H, period = AM.</li>
              <li>If \( H = 12 \): standard hour = 12, period = PM.</li>
              <li>If \( 13 \le H \le 23 \): standard hour = H − 12, period = PM.</li>
            </ol>
          </div>
          <p><strong>Example:</strong> 1730</p>
          <ul>
            <li>H = 17, M = 30</li>
            <li>17 ≥ 13 → 17 − 12 = 5, period = PM</li>
            <li>Result: <strong>5:30 PM</strong></li>
          </ul>

          <h3>Formula: standard → military time</h3>
          <div class="formula-box text-sm">
            <p><strong>Given:</strong> hour h (1–12), minute m (0–59), and AM/PM</p>
            <ol>
              <li>If period = AM and h = 12 → H = 0.</li>
              <li>If period = AM and h &lt; 12 → H = h.</li>
              <li>If period = PM and h = 12 → H = 12.</li>
              <li>If period = PM and h &lt; 12 → H = h + 12.</li>
              <li>Military time = \( H \times 100 + m \), padded to 4 digits.</li>
            </ol>
          </div>
          <p><strong>Example:</strong> 3:05 AM</p>
          <ul>
            <li>h = 3, m = 5, period = AM → H = 3</li>
            <li>Military time = 3 × 100 + 5 = 305 → <strong>0305</strong></li>
          </ul>

          <h3>Common edge cases</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>12:00 AM</strong> → 0000</li>
            <li><strong>12:00 PM</strong> → 1200</li>
            <li><strong>11:59 PM</strong> → 2359</li>
            <li><strong>Midnight at end of day</strong> → sometimes written as 2400</li>
          </ul>

          <h2>Where military time is used</h2>
          <p>Military time avoids ambiguity and is widely used in:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Military &amp; aviation</strong> – mission plans, flight schedules, NOTAMs.</li>
            <li><strong>Healthcare</strong> – medical charts, medication times, shift schedules.</li>
            <li><strong>Transportation</strong> – trains, buses, ships, and international timetables.</li>
            <li><strong>Emergency services</strong> – police, fire, EMS dispatch logs.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="prose mt-10">
          <h2>FAQ: Military time conversion</h2>

          <h3>How do you say military time out loud?</h3>
          <p>Military time is usually spoken as separate digits:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>0000 → “zero hundred hours” or “midnight”</li>
            <li>0905 → “zero nine zero five” or “oh nine oh five”</li>
            <li>1730 → “seventeen thirty hours”</li>
            <li>2100 → “twenty one hundred hours”</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>Is 2400 the same as 0000?</h3>
          <p>Yes, both refer to midnight, but they are used slightly differently:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>0000</strong> – start of a new day.</li>
            <li><strong>2400</strong> – end of the current day (often in schedules).</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>Why do hospitals and airlines use military time?</h3>
          <p>Because it removes ambiguity. “7:00” could mean AM or PM, but “1900” is always 7:00 PM. This reduces the risk of dangerous or costly mistakes in critical environments.</p>
